	abstract = {Abstract Atmospheric chemistry models?components in models that simulate air pollution and climate change?are computationally expensive. Previous studies have shown that machine-learned atmospheric chemical solvers can be orders of magnitude faster than traditional integration methods but tend to suffer from numerical instability. Here, we present a modeling framework that reduces error accumulation compared to previous work while maintaining computational efficiency. Our approach is novel in that it (1) uses a recurrent training regime that results in extended ({\textgreater}1 week) simulations without exponential error accumulation and (2) can reversibly compress the number of modeled chemical species by {\textgreater}80\% without further decreasing accuracy. We observe an {\textasciitilde}260? speedup ({\textasciitilde}1,900? with specialized hardware) compared to the traditional solver. We use random initial conditions in training to promote general applicability across a wide range of atmospheric conditions. For ozone (concentrations ranging from 0?70 ppb), our model predictions over a 24-hr simulation period match those of the reference solver with median error of 2.7 and {\textless}19 ppb error across 99\% of simulations initialized with random noise. Error can be significantly higher in the remaining 1\% of simulations, which include extreme concentration fluctuations simulated by the reference model. Results are similar for total particulate matter (median error of 16 and {\textless}32 ?g/m3 across 99\% of simulations with concentrations ranging from 0?150 ?g/m3). Finally, we discuss practical implications of our modeling framework and next steps for improvements. The machine learning models described here are not yet replacements for traditional chemistry solvers but represent a step toward that goal.},
